3 UAN - Territories with Archaeological Findings The spatial delimitation of UAN reflects the state of contemporary knowledge of the territory in terms of archaeology
and is divided into four categories: UAN I - Territories with a positive and further safe prediction of archaeological finds; UAN II - Territories in
which the presence of archaeological finds has not yet been positively proven but certain indications suggest it: the probability of archaeological finds is 51-100%; UAN
III - Territories in which it has not yet been recognised and Positive evidence of the occurrence of archaeological finds and no indications so
far, but the area in question may have been settled or otherwise used by man and therefore there is a 50% probability of the
occurrence of archaeological finds. It is therefore the territory of the whole Czech Republic except UAN I, II and IV; UAN IV - territory
where there is an unrealistic probability of occurrence of archaeological finds - all excavated territories - quarries, brickworks, sandboxes, etc. Â§ 21 - 24
of Act No 20/1987Sb. - The provisions of the Act must be observed throughout the area of interest in categories UAN I - III.

5. A brief history of ZubÅÃ­ Municipality
The local name tooth is interpreted as "the place where the dentists are." The accuracy of
the interpretation is justified by interpretations of similar local names such as Deer, Trout, etc. (HosÃ¡k
- Å rÃ¡mek 1980, 800). The oldest written record attesting to the existence of the village
dates from 1348, when Jimram of Stone and his sons transfer among other goods the village
of ZubÅÃ­ to the ownership of the brothers JeÅ¡ka and BeneÅ¡ of Boskovic (Chytil et al.
1856, 1). In 1358, the Moravian Margrave, Jan JindÅich of Luxembourg, acquires part of BystÅice and
other belongings from Jesek. While ZubÅÃ­ is not mentioned by name, it can be assumed that
it was also among these estates, since two years later (1360) the Moravian Margrave John is
transferring his share of BystÅice along with other villages of Janu from Boskovic, and ZubÅÃ­ is
mentioned at this event (HosÃ¡k 2004, 71). In the years that followed, the tooth again came
into Luxembourg's possession. In 1384, Margrave YoÅ¡t MoravskÃ½ (Luxembourg) gives the castle PyÅ¡olec in the fief,
with works by BystÅice and several villages (among them ZubÅÃ­) to Heralto of Kunsttate. Heralt gives
these goods sometime before 1417 as collateral to Blud of the Rabbits. After Heralto's death, Bocek
Kuna of Kunsttate and Podebrad (ibid, 335) is paying the fortunes back. Then the pyschlical and
torrential estates are taken over by the gentlemen of Pernstein (ibid, 71). In 1585, Jan and
MaxmilÃ¡n of PernÅ¡tejna sell the New Town estate, which then included ZubÅÃ­, to William Dubsky of
TÅebomislic. Since then, the fate of the tooth has been closely linked to the New City.
After 1620, the estate of the lords of TÅebomyslice was confiscated and subsequently sold to Prince
Francis Cardinal of DitrichÅ¡tejn in 1624. His heir Maximilian of DitrichÅ¡tejn sells it in 1638 to
Simon Kratzer of Schensberg. His son, Francis Maximilian, runs the estates after Shimon's death. But he
mismanaged the acquired property so badly that he mortgaged the estate, and was subsequently withdrawn by
the court's ruling. Thus, 1691 falls back into the hands of the DitrichÅ¡tejn. They then advance
the estates to the so-called MariÃ¡nskÃ© Å¡koly v Brno (Foundation Institute of Nobles) (ibid, 74). According
to the municipal law of 1849, the municipality has become the lowest unit of political administration
since 1850. On the basis of this law, a new political and judicial organization of the
crown countries is approved in 1854, according to which the district general and the judicial district
of New Town are proclaimed (Fuks 2010, 1). As part of a large-scale merging of municipalities
in the 2nd century, Zubor was annexed to the New Town in Moravia in 1980.
It regained its autonomy following a change in political circumstances in 1992 (Freedom 2001, 208).
From a technical point of view, the following objectives were initially set:
1. Demonstration or exclusion of the presence of archaeological finds in the
area of interest. 2. Reconstruction of the two-way genesis of historical overburden,
intensity and character of settlement. 3. The issue of moving luxury and
exceptional objects in space and time, the problem of imports. Methodology of
research The exact procedure and method of rescue archaeological research was chosen
according to the situation and timing of the construction. Interferences with archaeological
terrains were line digs for sewers. In selected locations, advance research was
conducted in regular probes measuring 1.5 m x 1.5 m. In justified
cases, the probe was expanded to approximately 1.5 x 2.2 m. Excavation
work was performed manually from the current ground surface to the natural
contexts. Objects that showed up in the stratified strata levels were credibly
and photographically documented. After the fill was selected, the object was geodesically
targeted by a total station or unfavorably addressed to a geodesic-focused landmark.
The lower level of the probes was based on the design documentation
of the structure. After reaching the level of threat to archaeological situations,
a sketchy documentation of the resulting probe sections and their geodetic
focus by the total station was carried out. A so-called "form
description" of the stratigraphic units was used for writing the information,
according to the documentation standards in force at Pueblo - the
archaeological society, o.p.s. Specifically, the appropriate form was listed in the
field for each stratigraphic unit. Drawing documentation was done on a
scale of 1:20. The photographic documentation was carried out by the
Canon PowerShot SX120 IS apparatus. Movable findings were trialled in the
field and transported for laboratory processing. In parallel to the progress
of the field work, documentation was digitised and made up of
object sub-plans. Once the field research was completed, a record of findings, an
overall research plan, as well as field documentation were processed, linked by a
comprehensive database (Annex: Access DVD Database). Field research is concluded with a finding
report, which also includes the knowledge of each field for further scientific treatment.
Measurement documentation The research was focused by the geodet AleÅ¡ Kosslem, a total
station of the Topcon brand 3007N (Annex: List of Geodetic Points). Mgr. Jan
BaÅinka was responsible for directing the research. 7. Description of the situation S1
Description: Probe No 1, with a total dimension of 1,5 x 1,5 m,
was located on property with a p. The probe has been documented to
the level of the archaeological bedrock (stratigraphic unit 100) (Command: drawing No 1).
A hand-held cache of dusty brown earth, covered with grass turf (SJ 101),
showed that a good deal of the terrain had been damaged by recent
excavations of civil engineering (Command: Figure 2-3). Specifically, the excavations were for gas
pipes (SJ 500 and 501) and the excavation for telephone cable (SJ 502).
The preserved layer (Annex: Figure 4) is further described from the stratigraphically oldest
to the youngest layers of the terrain. On an archaeological substructure made up
of grey-beige clay (SJ 100), brown-grey, slightly plastic clay (SJ 115=119) containing
a homogeneous set of ceramic material of the 15th - 16th century.
This layer, forming the original surface of the terrain, was subsequently superimposed
by a 0,3 m-thick layer of fracture stone and clay (SJ 103)
containing ceramics of the 15th and 17th centuries. The situation described can
be interpreted as a convenient alteration of the communication surface, in order
to increase its viability. The following layers are made up of brown
earth piles (SJ 116, 112, 102) in which the ceramics of the
15th - 17th century were recorded in the displaced position (SJ 112).
S2 Description: Probe No 2, with a total dimension of 1.5 x 2.2 m,
was on a grassy island with a column of power line J from the
road connecting Zubra to New City in Moravia. It was about 9 m J
away from the JZ corner of house No. 19 (Attachment: plan 1). The probe
has been documented to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100) (Annex: Drawings No
6 - 7). A layer of gray-beige clay (SJ 100) has mounted an archaeological
bedrock with 15-16th century ceramic material (SJ 128). Overlayered with grayish-brown sandy clay
(SJ 141) and brown sandy clay (SJ 127) containing ceramics from the 15th
- 17th centuries, this layer represents the naturally shaped surface of the then
anthropogenic terrain. Genesis was interrupted by the introduction of grey-brown sandy clay with
a relatively large rock content (SJ 159). An excavator (SJ 509) of a
very irregular shape, for the construction of a drainage channel (SJ 700), was
later embedded in the lead. Its powder consists of layers of sandy clay
(SJ 143, 145, 146) and grey sandy gravel (SJ 111) with ceramics of
the 16th and 19th centuries. The gravel layer is similar in character to
layer No 128 and can be assumed to be secondary displaced sediment from
nearby areas. The situation described was subsequently superimposed by integral masses of sandy
clay and clay sand (SJ 103, 104, 105, 142, 147). The current surface
of the terrain is dusty brown earth covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
S3 Description: Probe No 3, with a total dimension of 1.5 x 2.5 m, was on
a grassed area between houses Nos 9 and 58 at a distance of 5 m S
from the SV corner of house No 58 and 4.5 m from the SV corner of
the entrance part of house No 9 (Annex: Plan No 1). The probe has been documented
to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100) (Request: Drawings No 3, 10). A brownish-grey, slightly
plastic clay (SJ 119=115), containing a homogeneous set of ceramic material, has mounted an archaeological bedrock
formed of grey-beige clay (SJ 100), containing a homogeneous set of ceramic material, 14th - 15th
century (Annex: Figure 23 - 25; Table 2). This layer, forming the original surface of the
terrain, was then overlaid by naturally emerging anthropogenic layers of brown plastic clay (SJ 114, 118).
Natural genesis was interrupted by the integral induction of layers of brown clay (SJ 117, 176,
120, 106). Layer 106 contained secondary displaced ceramics of the 14th - 20th century (Annex:
Figure 22, Table 2). During the 20th century, this layer broke the excavation of unspecified
civil engineering (SJ 511) and the excavation of the lime fire pit (SJ 504), which was
in superposition with the junior dig (SJ 503) for the gas pipeline. The trench cover (SJ
107) No 503 contained secondary displaced ceramics (14th - 15th and 19th centuries). The trench cover
(SJ 168) No 511 contained secondary displaced ceramics from the period (15th - 16th century). The
current surface of the terrain is dusty brown earth covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
S4 Description: Probe No 4, measuring a total of 1,5 x 1,5 m, was on a
grassy area in front of building No 25, at a distance of 13 m S from
its From corner and 10 m east-south-east from the In corner of building No 105 (Annex:
Plan No 1). The probe has been documented to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100)
(Annex: Drawing No 4). A layer of tiny (up to 3 cm) fracture rock (SJ 134)
has mounted an archaeological bedrock made up of grey-beige clay clay (SJ 100). It is a
strengthening adjustment of the communication area. A layer of brownish grey clay sand (SJ 133) overlaps
the stony layer, most likely forming deposits resulting from the use of layer No 134 as
a walking surface. This interpretation is supported by the subsequent development of the terrain, when a
similar situation recurs. Layer No 133 is superimposed over the entire surface of the probe by
a layer of fracture stone with an admixture of aluminium sand (SJ 132, contains 15th-century ceramics)
on which layers of aluminium sand (SJ 131, 130) are mounted. It can be assumed that
this is again a strengthening of the communication area and proof of its use. The downstream
layers are made up of a layer of mortar (SJ 126), building rubble with carbons (SJ
125) and building rubble (SJ 124). This horizon can be interpreted as a targeted distribution of
a damaged structure that has ceased to serve its purpose. Probably after the fire. As illustrated
by the 1835 map of the Stable Cadastra, there has indeed been a development in the
past in close proximity to the probe (Annex: Plan 2). In layers 124 and 125,
ceramics dating back to the 16th century were found (Annex: Figures 20-21, Table 3), layer
125 also contained Renaissance duck from 2nd to 16th tables. (Annex: Figure 19; Table 1.
The destructive horizon is overlaid by layers of recent bindings (SJ 123, 122, 121). The
current surface of the terrain is dusty brown earth covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
S5 Description: Probe No 5, with a total dimension of 1,5 x 1,5 m,
was located in S part of the property with p. The probe has been
documented to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100) (Request: Drawing No 5). A
total of four integral excavations have been ploughed into the archaeological bedrock, which is
made up of grey-beige clay (SJ 100). Neither was fully uncovered because they encroached

with a depth of 0.2m was uncovered in the probe's JZ year. Its filling
was a slightly plastic beige-brown clay (SJ 135), containing ceramic material dating back to
the 15th - 16th tables. In the probe's SZ year, a part of the
indefinable-shaped excavation (SJ 506) with a recorded depth of 0.16m was uncovered. Its filling
was a slightly plastic beige-brown-brown clay (SJ 139). A portion of an indeterminate-shape excavation
(SJ 507) with a recorded depth of 0.12 m was uncovered in the probe's
SV year. Its filling was a slightly plastic beige-brown sandy clay (SJ 140). In
the probe's JV of the year, part of an indeterminate-shape excavation (SJ 510) was
uncovered at a depth of 0.2 m. Its fill was dusty black brown clay
(SJ 136). These excavations have superimposed recent piles of sandy clay (SJ 138, 137)
with secondary displaced ceramics of the 15th - 20th century. The current surface
of the terrain is dusty brown clay, covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
S6 Description: Probe No 6, with a total dimension of 1,5 x 1,5
m, was located in S part of the bait box between buildings No
e. 42 and No 53. It was 3 m northeast of S corner
of building No. 42 and 11,5 m Z towards S corner of building
No p. 53 (Attribution: plan 1). Due to the root system of a
nearby tree, only the SZ field probe has been excavated to the level
of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100) (Annex: Drawing No 8). A layer of pure
sand (SJ 157) and gravel sand (SJ 154) with 15th-century ceramic material had
been mounted on a bedrock formed by grey-beige clay clay (SJ 100). I
believe that these are fluvial sediments formed during torrential rains by flushing
coarser soil particles from higher ground areas. The refractive rock layer (SJ
155) would then constitute a makeshift modification of the communication surface, which
was again overlaid with other silts. These sediments overlap with sand-loam (SJ)
150, 149). The current surface of the terrain is dark black sandy clay
(SJ 148) containing secondary displaced ceramics of the 16th - 17th century.
S7 Description: Probe No 7, with a total dimension of 1.5 x 1.5 m, was between
building Nos 14 and 37, at a distance of 5 m S from the corner of
house No P 37 and 15 m JV from the corner of house No P 14
(Annex: Plan No 1). The probe has been documented to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ
100) (Annex: Drawing No 9). A bedrock of grey-beige clay (SJ 100) has developed a soil-forming
horizon (SJ 164) of beige-grey-brown plastic clay. A cultural layer of dark grey-black clay (SJ 166)
has formed on it. Its development was interrupted by a build-up of grey-black sandy clay (SJ
166), which contained ceramics dating back to the 15th - 16th century period. On it immediately
mounted layers of clay sand (SJ 162) and sandy clay (SJ 167). The unevenness of the
terrain was subsequently compensated by a layer of beige-brown clay (SJ 161), which in places
reached up to 0.3 m. A layer of black-brown sandy clay (SJ 160, found two
horseshoes) and a layer of brown sandy clay (SJ 159) containing ceramics reached the 17th
- 19th table. The latter surface was subsequently altered by adding gravel to the dirt
(SJ 158) to enhance the terrain. A layer of beige-brown sandy clay (SJ 165) was
later added to this layer, which again flattened the terrain into a relative robin. The
current surface of the terrain is dusty brown earth covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
S8 Description: Probe No 8, measuring a total of 1.5 x 2 m It was laid
at the CA side of house No 24. The distance from In the corner of the
opposite house, No 74, was about 8 m J towards (Schedule: Schedule No 1). The probe
has been documented to the level of archaeological bedrock (SJ 100) (Request: Drawing No 11). In
a depression of bedrock formed by the outcrop of rock (SJ 100), remnants of fluvial sediments
(SJ 174, 173), containing ceramic material of the 15th - 16th century, were preserved. On the
outcrop of rock, there was then about a 0,25m-thick weight of dark brown sandy earth (SJ
172). According to the ceramic material, the weight can be dated to the 19th century, and
this is indicative of the field modifications at the No.8 probe sites that resulted in the
removal of the original deposits. Layer 172 was broken by a sewer trench (SJ 512) overhauled
younger, sandy clay (SJ 178, 175) and cinders (SJ 171). A recent excavator (SJ
513) for the gas line is lubricated into the co-layers. The current surface
of the terrain is dusty brown earth covered with grass turf (SJ 101).
Assessment of research results Brief summary of findings on the questions asked 1.
Demonstration or exclusion of the presence of archaeological finds in the area of
interest. Archaeological research conducted in 2013 documented very well-preserved archaeological situations in the
U.K. Teeth at the New Town in Moravia. The archaeological situations uncovered demonstrated
the intense use of the interest space from the 14th century to the
present. 2. Reconstruction of the two-way genesis of historical overburden, intensity and character
of settlement. Archaeological research has provided evidence of the continuous settlement of this
space from the 14th century to the present. The oldest ceramic material was
found in the form of intrusions in the cultural stratum of the 16th
century (SJ 115=119), in the navage of the 20th century (SJ 106), or
in the burlap (SJ 107) of the recent excavation of engineering networks (SJ
503). Furthermore, adjustments to communication surfaces in the bait compartment during the 15th
century period (SJ 132) and the 17th century period (SJ 113) have been
documented. A document of construction works (SJ 124, 125, 126) or a 19th-century
stone drainage canal (SJ 700) has also been identified. Equally important is
the evidence of erosive accumulation processes caused by the elemental activity of
water in the early modern period (SJ 128, 151, 153, 154, 156,
157). 3. The issue of the movement of luxury and exceptional objects
in space and time, the problem of imports The archaeological research that
took place in the ZubÅÃ­ intravilÃ¡n municipality, was obtained by a set
of movable archaeological artifacts. These were mainly fragments of common kitchen and
table ceramics from the 14th - 15th century period to the present.
In general, from the end of the 15th century to the mid-16th century, there are significant
changes in ceramics. These are both shape and technology changes. Ceramic clay becomes finer with less,
or no, addition of stones and so-called blades. The spray is mainly applied to larger vessels
with thicker walls. Along with the ceramic, the shape of the vessels changes, with the maximum
aneurysm from the top third of the vessel moving to its approximate half and the walls
tending to be thinner (Pajer 1983, 21; VaÅeka 2008, 41). In addition to vessels that were
common as early as the Middle Ages (e.g. pots with lids, jugs, tripods, etc.), new ceramic
shapes are beginning to appear and expand. First of all, there are bowls with saucer-shaped sub-regions
and, during the 2nd mid-16th century, the first saucer-shaped ones. Large pans, cream, or bakers (Pajer
1983, 23; VaÅeka 2008, 42) also appear. At this time of year, along with the commonly
used rye and smoked pottery, glazed (souped) pottery is increasingly being used. New decorating techniques such
as painting with clay (on an overhead shard, or on a spray) or using multiple different
glazes at the same time on a single vessel (e.g. flaming, embedding, or pigmentation) also
appear hand in hand with these changes (VaÅeka 2008, 42). With the advent and development
of new techniques, however, some of the older decorative motifs, such as ploughing, or scoring,
are lost (Pajer 1983, 59, 64). In addition to the fragments of vessels, a set
of Renaissance tile fragments was recovered. This finding illustrates the transformation of the residential part
of the village house, with older ovens with open-air operation into the living room being
replaced by a tiled stove (often combined with a furnace) with an operating space normally
situated in the adjoining hall. This changes the shape and quality of housing. In our
territory, the change in question occurs mostly during the 16th century (VaÅeka 2008, 41). A
fraction of a duck was found in Probe 4 (SJ 125) whose front heating wall
is decorated with a geometric ornament complete with a plant motif (Annex: Figure 19; Table
1). This decoration was very popular in the region. A similar motive (Annex: Figure 26)
was found in the municipality of Jimramov (district Å½ÄÃ¡r nad SÃ¡zavou) in archaeological research carried
out between 2012 - 2013 (HuÅ¡tÃ¡k 2014, 14), or in the municipality of BlaÅ¾ejovice u
Rozsoch (district Å½ÄÃ¡r nad SÃ¡zavou) in research in 2014 (Annex: Figure 27; Baier 2014, 10).
Archaeological research in 2013, documented the vast and well-preserved archaeological situation in the U.K.
Teeth at the New Town in Moravia. The archaeological situations uncovered demonstrated the intense
use of the interest space from the 14th century to the present. The evidence
was the continuity of some of the communication areas in the bait room up
to the 15th century, the novelty of the construction works, the drainage stone channel
from the 19th century, or the marked traces of erosion accumulation processes during the
early modern period. Although the rescue research has been carried out, we cannot disregard
the fact that we have explored an area immediately threatened by construction. We can
state with a certain degree of probability that archaeological situations can be maintained around
the research area, which are only preserved by a layer of novelistic treatments. In
the event of further interventions in the field, the rescue research resulting from
the abovementioned laws on the protection of cultural heritage should again be envisaged.
